uce unexpected results.","id":"CHOICE-001-s1-0","rule_id":"CHOICE-001","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No governing-law clause detected"},{"description":"The contract does not allocate ownership of intellectual property.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no IP-ownership clause)"},"explanation":"Without an IP-ownership clause, default copyright and patent rules apply: under 17 U.S.C. § 201, copyright vests in the author/employee unless work-for-hire or assignment applies.","id":"IPDATA-001-s1-0","rule_id":"IPDATA-001","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-17-usc-101","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"17 U.S.C. § 101 — Definitions (work made for hire)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/101"},{"id":"stat-17-usc-201","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"17 U.S.C. § 201","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/201"}],"title":"No IP-ownership clause detected"},{"description":"Neither 'indemnify' nor 'hold harmless' appears in the document.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no indemnification language)"},"explanation":"Most commercial contracts allocate risk through an indemnification clause. The absence leaves the parties to default tort and contract law for any third-party claims.","id":"RISK-001-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-001","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No indemnification clause detected"},{"description":"Vaulytica did not find a limitation-of-liability clause.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no LoL clause)"},"explanation":"Without a limitation-of-liability clause, exposure is bounded only by what the parties can prove in damages. Most commercial contracts cap liability.","id":"RISK-005-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No limitation-of-liability clause detected"},{"description":"No Effective Date is named, defined, or stated near the top of this Agreement.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no Effective Date reference matched)"},"explanation":"Most contracts identify a starting point that other date references rely on. Without it, relative terms like 'within 30 days after the Effective Date' have no anchor.","id":"STRUCT-002-s1-0","recommendation":"Add an Effective Date — either in the preamble ('dated as of [date]'), as a defined term, or as an explicit 'Effective Date: [date]' line.","rule_id":"STRUCT-002","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No Effective Date found"},{"description":"Used but not defined: Best Rating, Constellation Casualty Insurance Co, Employers Liability Disease, Wayne Brokerage.","document_position":1572,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1583,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":1572,"text":"Best Rating"},"explanation":"Title-Case phrases in a contract usually signal a defined term. When they aren't defined, readers must guess at the intended meaning. Either define them or use lowercase if the term is intended in its ordinary sense.","id":"STRUCT-006-s1-1572","recommendation":"Add a definition for each genuinely defined term, or change the casing if the phrase is being used in its ordinary sense.","rule_id":"STRUCT-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Undefined Title-Case terms: 4"},{"description":"The contract does not state a path to terminate for material breach.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no for-cause termination)"},"explanation":"Without a for-cause termination path, parties must rely on common-law material-breach doctrines, which are jurisdiction-dependent.","id":"TERM-002-s1-0","rule_id":"TERM-002","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No termination-for-cause clause detected"},{"description":"The contract does not state what happens upon termination.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no effect-of-termination clause)"},"explanation":"An effect-of-termination clause spells out the rights and obligations that survive, the return or destruction of materials, and the wind-down rules.","id":"TERM-005-s1-0","rule_id":"TERM-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No effect-of-termination clause detected"},{"description":"The document does not state where disputes must be brought.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no venue clause)"},"explanation":"Without a venue clause, default venue rules apply (in federal court, 28 U.S.C. § 1391). A clear forum-selection clause avoids ambiguity.","id":"CHOICE-003-s1-0","rule_id":"CHOICE-003","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-28-usc-1391","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"28 U.S.C. § 1391 (venue generally)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/28/1391"}],"title":"No venue / forum clause detected"},{"description":"COMMERCIAL GENERAL LIABILITY — Constellation Casualty Insurance Co. — NAIC 22334 — CGL-2026-447821 — 2026-01-01 — 2027-01-01 Each Occurrence: $1,000,000","document_position":1213,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1365,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":1213,"text":"COMMERCIAL GENERAL LIABILITY — Constellation Casualty Insurance Co. — NAIC 22334 — CGL-2026-447821 — 202